ing experience, Preda’s fascinating ethnography investigates how ordinary people take up financial trading, how they form communities of their own behind their computer screens, and how electronic finance encourages them to trade more and more frequently. Along the way, Preda finds the answer to the paradox of amateur trading—the traders aren’t so much seeking monetary rewards in the financial markets, rather the trading itself helps them to fulfill their own personal goals and aspirations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aElectronic trading of securitiesxPsychological aspects. 0aElectronic trading of securities. 0aInvestmentsxDecision making. 0aInvestments. 0aOnline stockbrokers. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aelectronic markets.  aethnography.  afinance.  alogic of trading.  asocial institutions.  asocial lives.  atraders.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022642734840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226427515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226427515/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles